 the Jewish community about the transmission of tradition.Focusing on the Babylonian Talmud, produced in the rabbinic academies of late ancient Mesopotamia, Vidas analyzes key passages to show how the Talmud's creators contrasted their own voice with that of their predecessors. He also examines Zoroastrian, Christian, and mystical Jewish sources to reconstruct the debates and wide-ranging conversations that shaped the Talmud's literary and intellectual character.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJewish lawxInterpretation and construction. 0aReligionxJudaismxGeneral. 0aTalmudxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Talmud.2bisacsh  aAmoraic tradition.  aBabylonian Talmud.  aBava Qamma.  aChristian literature.  aChristian sources.  aChristianity.  aChristians.  aHekhalot literature.  aHekhalot tradition.  aIsrael.  aJewish culture.  aJewish genealogy.  aJewish history.  aJewish people.  aJewish tradition.  aJews.  aJudaism.  aMesopotamia.  aOral Torah.  aPalestinian Talmud.  aRav Yehuda.  aSar ha-Torah narrative.  aScripture.  aTorah study.  aWritten Torah.  aZoroastrian literature.  aZoroastrian ritual.  aZoroastrian sources.  aanonymous layer.  aapodictic rulings.  aattributed rulings.  aauthority.  acomposition.  adialectic.  adiscontinuity.  agenealogical knowledge.  agenealogical tradition.  aintellectual history.  alayered structure.  aliterary design.  aliturgy.  amystical Jewish sources.  aoral tradition.  arabbinic culture.  arabbis.  arecitation.  areligious text.  asacred texts.  ascholarship.  aself-definition.  aself-presentation.  astam.  asugya.  asugyot.  atanna'im.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z9783110